      "culturalSignificance": "Elder was central to Norse and Germanic folk medicine and magic, a tradition that continued in rural Scandinavia and Germany into the 20th century. The requirement to ask permission before cutting reflects animistic beliefs that trees house spirits deserving respect. Elder wine and elderflower cordials were traditional drinks for celebrations and healing. The prohibition against burning elder wood (still observed in some rural areas) preserves ancient taboos. Elder's presence in folklore as a gateway to the fairy realm influenced later European fairy tales."
